ce:section.ce:para:
To further explore the effect of NCDs on the EEU of acetogens, Sporomusa ovata was used to investigate its transcriptional expression differences with and without NCDs1:1 at the cathodic potential of −0.4 V (vs. SHE) (Fig. 4
                           A, B). Cathodic current generation in NCDs1:1-modified MESs was higher than that without modified. The comparison result was consistent with that obtained in mixed-culture MESs (see supplementary material and Fig. 2A). The result suggested that NCDs1:1 modification enhanced the ability of acetogens to uptake extracellular electrons from the cathode. As shown in Fig. 4A, NCDs1:1 modification upregulated 835 genes and downregulated 230 genes in S. ovata-MESs, with the cathode as the sole electron donor (FC >2 or <0.5, p < 0.05). In this study, 20 genes encoding cytochromes were detected in electric-autotrophic S. ovata. 14 of these genes were upregulated with NCDs1:1 modification, including 2 genes encoding cytochrome bd (cydA and cydB), 2 genes encoding cytochrome b (cybH and SOV_3c02070), and 10 genes encoding cytochrome c (SOV_2c11600, SOV_2c11650, SOV_2c11670, SOV_2c11690, SOV_6c01070, SOV_2c11660, SOV_6c01090, SOV_5c02910, SOV_2c11700, and SOV_6c01080) (Fig. 4B). Subcellular localization prediction indicated that all genes encoding cytochromes were located in the cytoplasmic membrane, except for 3 genes with unknown locations (SOV_2c11600, SOV_2c11690, and SOV_6c01090) and 2 genes located in the periplasm (SOV_6c01070 and SOV_2c11700) (Table 2
                           ). These genes did not possess the β-barrel structure that connects outer membrane cytochromes to periplasmic cytochromes, but they all contained transmembrane fragments (1–15) (Table 2). Moreover, NCDs1:1 with the particle size of 6.2 ± 0.6 nm distributed inside and outside of bacterial cells (see supplementary material). This implied that the internalized NCDs1:1 may interact with membrane-bound cytochromes in acetogens, thereby inducing their expression. Notably, under cathodic electro-autotrophic conditions (−0.4 V vs. SHE), the expression of cydA and cydB was significantly upregulated by 1478.1 % and 1169.0 %, respectively, compared with cathodic H2-autotrophic S. ovata (−0.7 V vs. SHE). In contrast, the expression of cybH was downregulated by 48.6 % (Fig. 4C). These findings suggested that cydAB and cybH may play an important role in direct and indirect EEU of S. ovata, respectively. The upregulated expression of cydAB and cybH in S. ovata-MESs induced by NCDs1:1 supported the hypothesis that NCDs1:1 enhanced the EEU and consequently improved the performance of MESs through the interaction between NCDs1:1 and electron-transport-related components.
